steps.answer:
We can think of the vase as a cone with its tip chopped off on top.

[asy]
size(150);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));
path base = ellipse((0,0),16/3,10/3);
draw(base);
draw((8,0)--(0,0)--(-2,10)--cycle,dashed);
draw((0,0)--(-10/3,0));
fill((0,0)--(8,0)--(-2,10)--cycle,gray(0.7));
draw((0,0)--(0,10));
label("$8$",(0,5),E);
label("$5$",(4,0),S);
label("$30$",(0,10),NW);
[/asy]

We see that in order to generate the vase, we rotate an ellipse with equation $\frac{x^2}{8^2}+\frac{y^2}{5^2}=1$ about its minor axis.  Consider a disk with thickness $\triangle y$ lying inside the vase.

[asy]
size(150);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.8));
import graph;
path ellipse = graph(new pair(real x) {
return (8*cos(x),5*sin(x));
},0,2*pi)..cycle;
draw(ellipse);
draw(shift((0,10))*rotate(90)*ellipse);
draw((8,0)--(0,0)--(-2,10)--cycle,dashed);
draw((0,0)--(-10/3,0));
fill((0,0)--(8,0)--(-2,10)--cycle,gray(0.7));
fill((0,0)--(-2,10)--(-10/3,0)--cycle,gray(0.7));
draw((0,0)--(0,10));
dot((0,3.5));
dot((0,6));
label("$\Delta y$",(0,4.8),E);
label("$\Delta y$",(0,6.5),E);
[/asy]

Rotation would cause this disk to generate a larger vase, similar to how slicing a circle parallel to its base generates a disk with equal altitude and slant height; the difference is that the cross-sections are similar ellipses rather than similar circles.  We leave it to the reader to draw a diagram more revealing than words, in order to convince themselves of this fact.

The height of this disk is $\triangle y,$ the slant height is $30,$ and the radius of the cross-section is given by $f(\triangle y)=10-\frac{5(10-2\triangle y)}{8}.$

Thus, we can compute a formula for the volume of the vase:
\begin{align*}
\text{Volume} &= \int \text{Area} \cdot \text{height} \, d\triangle y \\
&= \int (f(\triangle y))^2 \pi \, d\triangle y \\
&= \int_0^5 \left(10-\frac{5(10-2\triangle y)}{8}\right)^2 \pi \, d\triangle y .
\end{align*}

Instead of evaluating this integral directly, we will take advantage of symmetry.  The expression depends only on $10-2\triangle y,$ so it is easier to perform our calculations with a substitution:  $u = 10-2\triangle y$ or $\triangle y = (10-u)/2.$  Also, when $u=0,$ $\triangle y = 5$ and when $u=10,$ $\triangle y = 0.$

So, the new integral is
\[ \int_0^{10} \left(10-\frac{5u}{8}\right)^2 \cdot \frac{1}{2} \cdot \pi \left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)du = \frac{\pi}{64}\int_0^{10} (5u-10)^2 \, du ,\]which expands to \[\frac{\pi}{64}\int_0^{10} (25u^2-100u+100) \, du.\]Integrating term by term, we compute $\frac{\pi}{64}\left[\frac{25u^3}{3}-50u^2+100u\right]\bigg|_0^{10}=\frac{\pi}{64}\left(\frac{25000}{3}\right)=\boxed{\frac{1250\pi}{192}}.$

We begin by drawing a rough sketch of the irregular octagon and labeling the given sides and diagonals.

[asy]
pair A=(0,0),B=(47,0),C=(76,27),D=(76,64),E=(47,91),F=(10,91),G=(0,64),H=(0,27);
label("$15$",(A+B)/2,SW);
label("$22$",(B+C)/2,SE);
label("$18$",(C+D)/2,SE);
label("$26$",(D+E)/2,NE);
label("$17$",(E+F)/2,NE);
label("$23$",(F+G)/2,NW);
label("$29$",(G+H)/2,NW);
label("$20$",(A+H)/2,W);
label("$40$",(B+D)/2,N);
label("$35$",(A+G)/2,W);
draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--G--H--cycle);
draw(A--C--E--G--cycle);
draw(A--D--B);
draw(G--C);
[/asy]

It is helpful to divide the octagon into triangles and quadrilaterals using the diagonals. We start by considering the diagonal of length 40 meters. There are two possibilities for which two nonconsecutive vertices it connects, but since it is perpendicular to the other given diagonal, we choose the vertices that share a side with it to simplify the diagram.

[asy]
pair A=(0,0),B=(47,0),C=(76,27),D=(76,64),E=(47,91),F=(10,91),G=(0,64),H=(0,27),X=(47,64);
label("$15$",(A+B)/2,SW);
label("$22$",(B+C)/2,SE);
label("$18$",(C+D)/2,SE);
label("$26$",(D+E)/2,NE);
label("$17$",(E+F)/2,NE);
label("$23$",(F+G)/2,NW);
label("$29$",(G+H)/2,NW);
label("$20$",(A+H)/2,W);
label("$40$",(B+D)/2,N);
label("$35$",(A+G)/2,W);
draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--G--H--cycle);
draw(A--C--E--G--cycle);
draw(A--D--B);
draw(G--C);
draw(X--D,dotted);
[/asy]

The diagonal of length 40 meters divides the octagon into two quadrilaterals and one triangle. We can find the length of the horizontal segment in the dotted line by using the Pythagorean theorem. Let $x$ be the length we are looking for. Then applying Pythagoras on right triangle $ABX$ gives us $x^2+15^2=22^2$, or $x=19$. Similarly, applying Pythagoras on right triangle $DXC$ gives us $(40-x)^2+18^2=26^2$, or $x=13$. Thus we have found that $BX=19$ meters and $CX=27$ meters.

[asy]
pair A=(0,0),B=(47,0),C=(76,27),D=(76,64),E=(47,91),F=(10,91),G=(0,64),H=(0,27),X=(47,64);
label("$15$",(A+B)/2,SW);
label("$22$",(B+C)/2,SE);
label("$18$",(C+D)/2,SE);
label("$26$",(D+E)/2,NE);
label("$17$",(E+F)/2,NE);
label("$23$",(F+G)/2,NW);
label("$29$",(G+H)/2,NW);
label("$20$",(A+H)/2,W);
label("$40$",(B+D)/2,N);
label("$35$",(A+G)/2,W);
draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--G--H--cycle);
draw(A--C--E--G--cycle);
draw(A--D--B);
draw(G--C);
draw(X--D,dotted);
label("$19$",(X+B)/2,S);
label("$27$",(X+C)/2,NE);
[/asy]

Next we consider the diagonal of length 35 meters.

[asy]
pair A=(0,0),B=(47,0),C=(76,27),D=(76,64),E=(47,91),F=(10,91),G=(0,64),H=(0,27),X=(47,64),Y=(23,27);
label("$15$",(A+B)/2,SW);
label("$22$",(B+C)/2,SE);
label("$18$",(C+D)/2,SE);
label("$26$",(D+E)/2,NE);
label("$17$",(E+F)/2,NE);
label("$23$",(F+G)/2,NW);
label("$29$",(G+H)/2,NW);
label("$20$",(A+H)/2,W);
label("$40$",(B+D)/2,N);
label("$35$",(A+G)/2,W);
draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--G--H--cycle);
draw(A--C--E--G--cycle);
draw(A--D--B);
draw(G--C);
draw(X--D,dotted);
draw(A--G);
draw(Y--C,dotted);
label("$19$",(X+B)/2,S);
label("$27$",(X+C)/2,NE);
label("$35$",(A+G+Y)/3,NE);
[/asy]

The diagonal of length 35 meters divides the octagon into two triangles and one hexagon. We can find the areas of these polygons separately and then add them up to find the total area of the octagon. Let's begin with the larger triangle.

The base of this triangle is the diagonal of length 40 meters, which we have already found to be 19 and 27 meters. We can find the height by using the formula for the area of a triangle, $A=\frac{1}{2}bh$. Let $h$ be the height we are looking for. Then we have $A=\frac{1}{2}(19+27)h$, or $h=\frac{35}{2}$. Thus the area of the larger triangle is $\frac{1}{2}(40)\left(\frac{35}{2}\right)=\frac{35}{2}\cdot 20=350$ square meters.

Next, let's look at the smaller triangle.

[asy]
pair A=(0,0),B=(47,0),C=(76,27),D=(76,64),E=(47,91),F=(10,91),G=(0,64),H=(0,27),X=(47,64),Y=(23,27),Z=(52,27);
label("$15$",(A+B)/2,SW);
label("$22$",(B+C)/2,SE);
label("$18$",(C+D)/2,SE);
label("$26$",(D+E)/2,NE);
label("$17$",(E+F)/2,NE);
label("$23$",(F+G)/2,NW);
label("$29$",(G+H)/2,NW);
label("$20$",(A+H)/2,W);
label("$40$",(B+D)/2,N);
label("$35$",(A+G)/2,W);
draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--G--H--cycle);
draw(A--C--E--G--cycle);
draw(A--D--B);
draw(G--C);
draw(X--D,dotted);
draw(A--G);
draw(Y--C,dotted);
draw(X--Z);
label("$19$",(X+B)/2,S);
label("$27$",(X+C)/2,NE);
label("$35$",(A+G+Y)/3,NE);
label("$13$",(X+Z)/2,S);
[/asy]

Let $L$ be the length of the horizontal segment pointed to by the shorter side of the triangle (which is part of the side of length 17 meters). Then we have $L^2+K^2=18^2$, where $K$ is the length of the vertical segment and is the height of the triangle. To find $L$, notice that we can draw another diagonal that goes through the midpoint of the diagonal of length 35 meters and is perpendicular to it:

[asy]
pair A=(0,0),B=(47,0),C=(76,27),D=(76,64),E=(47,91),F=(10,91),G=(0,64),H=(0,27),X=(47,64),Y=(23,27),Z=(52,27),M=(23,64);
label("$15$",(A+B)/2,SW);
label("$22$",(B+C)/2,SE);
label("$18$",(C+D)/2,SE);
label("$26$",(D+E)/2,NE);
label("$17$",(E+F)/2,NE);
label("$23$",(F+G)/2,NW);
label("$29$",(G+H)/2,NW);
label("$20$",(A+H)/2,W);
label("$40$",(B+D)/2,N);
label("$35$",(A+G)/2,W);
draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--G--H--cycle);
draw(A--C--E--G--cycle);
draw(A--D--B);
draw(G--C);
draw(X--D,dotted);
draw(A--G);
draw(Y--C,dotted);
draw(X--Z);
draw(C--M,dotted);
label("$19$",(X+B)/2,S);
label("$27$",(X+C)/2,NE);
label("$35$",(A+G+Y)/3,NE);
label("$13$",(X+Z)/2,S);
label("$8$",(M+X)/2,E);
draw((A+G)/2--(G+M)/2,dotted);
[/asy]

Here, we have also labeled the midpoint of the diagonal of length 35 meters as $M$. Since $CXM$ and $AXM$ are both right triangles, we can use Pythagoras to find $AX$, $AC$, and $XM$. We have $AX^2+18^2=35^2$, or $AX=29$, and $AC^2+23^2=35^2$, or $AC=12$. Then applying Pythagoras again on right triangle $XMZ$ gives us $XM^2+8^2=13^2$, or $XM=5$. Thus we have found that $L=12$ meters and $K=5\sqrt{3}$ meters.

Therefore, the area of the smaller triangle is $\frac{1}{2}(17)\left(5\sqrt{3}\right)=\frac{85\sqrt{3}}{2}$ square meters.

Finally, we look at the hexagon.

[asy]
pair A=(0,0),B=(47,0),C=(76,27),D=(76,64),E=(47,91),F=(10,91),G=(0,64),H=(0,27),X=(47,64),Y=(23,27),Z=(52,27),M=(23,64);
label("$15$",(A+B)/2,SW);
label("$22$",(B+C)/2,SE);
label("$18$",(C+D)/2,SE);
label("$26$",(D+E)/2,NE);
label("$17$",(E+F)/2,NE);
label("$23$",(F+G)/2,NW);
label("$29$",(G+H)/2,NW);
label("$20$",(A+H)/2,W);
label("$40$",(B+D)/2,N);
label("$35$",(A+G)/2,W);
draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--G--H--cycle);
draw(A--C--E--G--cycle);
draw(A--D--B);
draw(G--C);
draw(X--D,dotted);
draw(A--G);
draw(Y--C,dotted);
draw(X--Z);
draw(C--M,dotted);
label("$19$",(X+B)/2,S);
label("$27$",(X+C)/2,NE);
label("$35$",(A+G+Y)/3,NE);
label("$13$",(X+Z)/2,S);
draw(A--F--E--D--C--B--cycle);
[/asy]

This hexagon can be divided into two triangles by dropping a perpendicular from vertex $C$ to side $BE$.

[asy]
pair A=(0,0),B=(47,0),C=(76,27),D=(76,64),E=(47,91),F=(10,91),G=(0,64),H=(0,27),X=(47,64),Y=(23,27),Z=(52,27),M=(23,64),W=(67,0),V=(67,27);
label("$15$",(A+B)/2,SW);
label("$22$",(B+C)/2,SE);
label("$18$",(C+D)/2,SE);
label("$26$",(D+E)/2,NE);
label("$17$",(E+F)/2,NE);
label("$23$",(F+G)/2,NW);
label("$29$",(G+H)/2,NW);
label("$20$",(A+H)/2,W);
label("$40$",(B+D)/2,N);
label("$35$",(A+G)/2,W);
draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--G--H--cycle);
draw(A--C--E--G--cycle);
draw(A--D--B);
draw(G--C);
draw(X--D,dotted);
draw(A--G);
draw(Y--C,dotted);
draw(X--Z);
draw(C--M,dotted);
label("$19$",(X+B)/2,S);
label("$27$",(X+C)/2,NE);
label("$35$",(A+G+Y)/3,NE);
label("$13$",(X+Z)/2,S);
draw(A--F--E--D--C--B--cycle);
draw(C--V,dotted);
draw(C--W,dotted);
[/asy]

The area of the right triangle with base $BE$ is the same as the area of the smaller triangle we found earlier, which is $\frac{85\sqrt{3}}{2}$ square meters. To find the area of the left triangle, note that $CV=27$ meters and $CW=76-40-35=1$ meter. The height of the triangle is the distance from $C$ to $BE$, which is the same as the height of the right triangle we just found: $K=5\sqrt{3}$ meters. Therefore, the area of the left triangle is $\frac{1}{2}(27)(5\sqrt{3})=\frac{135\sqrt{3}}{2}$ square meters.

Finally, adding up the areas of the three polygons, we have: $350+\frac{85\sqrt{3}}{2}+\frac{135\sqrt{3}}{2}=\boxed{\frac{610+220\sqrt{3}}{2}}$ square meters.
